  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.3275" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <opener>Dear D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>. Schuchardt,</opener>

        <p>I was very glad to get your letter, that is postcard, tonight and to learn that the printing of your work is advancing so well. As soon as my tirage à part arrives I will send you a copy. I leave Paris on Monday for a week in the Cathedral city of Seez in the Orne and then I go for another week to Alençon in the same department where my work has been &amp; is being printed. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1294">De Charencey</persName> lives near there. 9 kilos off is a village of which at least the modern name <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Larré</hi> looks like <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Basque</ref>. I suppose <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">di</hi> in <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">
daidi</hi> to be potential. the indicative present singular both in Leiçarraga and in Biscayan is for the third person <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">
dagui</hi>. Campion is a member of the New Cortes, elected by the fueristas and Catholics of Pompilona or Iruñ (bonne ville de Pompée). He is going very soon to Donostia and will attack <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1054">
Arzác</persName> about his infidelity to me and Capanaga. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2939">Vinson</persName> in the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.4934">R. de L.</ref> published on Saturday repeats his false statement that Basque has neither a future tense nor a relative pronoun. He publishes at the same time some texts in which he points out the future! and in which one sees the relatives z<hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
ein</hi> and <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">n</hi> he translates devot içatea erranda (probably for <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">errenda</hi>) dieçaçuentçat by afin qu’il vous dise d'être encore etc: It means of course ”in order that it may render your devout state (or nature) yet more devout”. Dido now says that emazte is only an<note
            n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Dodgson setzt am linken Rand fort.</note> adjective of <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">emak</hi> = marâtre, that is = step[m]otherly.</p>
        <closer>
          <salute/>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1402">E. S. Dodgson</persName>. </signed>
          <note n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der rechten Seite.</note>
          <dateline>21 March 1893 Paris.</dateline>
        </closer>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
      </div>
